Fledgling economies and cryptocurrencies

Countries around the world are focusing more and more energy towards generating wealth leading them to take charge and an important position in world politics. Unlike before the industrial revolution when people used to work as artisans and farmers mostly, we’ve accumulated wealth, used it in research and further our nationalistic ideologies. 

Since economic stability translates to a better life for the inhabitants, governments are finding ways to enhance their trade through different means, mostly through exports of goods and labor. But with the advent of new technologies, more channels can be established by countries to accumulate wealth which could be a blessing specially for the ones lagging behind. Cryptocurrencies and block chain technology can be leveraged by these countries to make a huge positive impact on their economies. 

If we look at the table shown below we can identify how countries like Nauru, Marshall Islands or Tonga could have used the technologies to rise above in GDP ranking. Multiple ways can be employed, the simplest being owning the bitcoin or a more difficult one being, to set up mining facilities. 

Getting their hands dirty in this area also can be a huge risk for the governments as the technology is still not completely stable and a loss at a government scale (which is massive) can move them even further towards the darkness in terms of economic stability. Therefore, not most of the governments are taking investments in crypto very seriously. But some of them are planning to use technology in other ways, like China launching digital Yuan being the first major government backed cryptocoin.

Only time will tell how currencies around the world and blockchain technology can be used by smaller and larger governments for a further economic growth or a turnaround, but the success and failure stories coming out of them will have a lot for us to learn.
